#. type: Content of: <sections><section><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "Storage"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:21
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A difficult job of any Linux installation is to prepare the partitions to house\n"
"the Operating System. Each person has a different taste as to what should be on\n"
"a different partition and what shouldn't, or what file system to use. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:27
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The idea behind partitioning is to make some sort of separation between one set\n"
"of data and another. For instance, people have their <path>/boot</path>\n"
"separated from the root file system because they want to be able to hide the\n"
"<path>/boot</path> content from the system during regular operations. Or they\n"
"want to have <path>/home</path> separate because that would allow them to store\n"
"all user-specific information, settings and data on a different disk so they are\n"
"able to easily retrieve the data after an Operating System reinstallation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:37
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You can also choose to have a separate partition because you want to improve\n"
"performance by using a different file system tweaked to the use of the data\n"
"stored on the partition.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deciding on the partition scheme requires intimate knowledge of the file system:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "What files are stored where?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "How often are the files used? Read or written?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "What is the function of the system you are building?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "What features do the various file systems have?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Because this is something that comes with age (err, experience ;) your first,\n"
"second, third, ... attempt for a perfect scheme will undoubtedly fail. Lots of\n"
"people therefore opt for a simple partitioning scheme (like everything on a\n"
"single partition, with a separate partition for the swap<sup>1</sup> \n"
"information). Others attempt to use a more dynamical approach and use \n"
"<e>Volume Management</e>. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With Volume Management, you place a layer in between the partitions on the disk\n"
"and the file systems that hold your data. This layer can be used to combine\n"
"multiple partitions as if they were just a single one, or to use several logical\n"
"divisions on a single partition. Of course, Volume Management is much more than\n"
"that: it makes it easier to move data across partitions, shrink or grow file\n"
"systems, etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><note>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:72
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<sup>1</sup> Swap space is a specific location on the disk where the Linux \n"
"kernel can store memory pages (regions of data in memory, assigned for use by \n"
"processes or by the kernel itself) that will most likely not be used in a while.\n"
"The Linux kernel will, once your memory is completely filled (not sooner!), \n"
"move such memory pages to the swap location, thereby freeing internal memory \n"
"for other, more important memory pages.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "Designing a scheme"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should start designing a partitioning scheme for your system. Telling you\n"
"what partitioning scheme is best for you is impossible, but here are some\n"
"pointers:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    For each partition you want to create, ask around how much space the\n"
"    partition might get given the tools and services you want to install. Make\n"
"    sure you design each partition to be larger than the size given by others:\n"
"    growing a file system is <e>not</e> without danger.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Not all Linux file system locations are partitionable:\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li><ol><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:103
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        The <path>/etc</path>, <path>/lib</path>, <path>/bin</path> and\n"
"        <path>/sbin</path> locations must stay on the root file system as they\n"
"        are required by the Operating System under any circumstances. This is\n"
"        because they are needed to be able to mount other partitions on the file\n"
"        system.\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li><ol><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:110
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        Only directories can be separated from a file system. Each separation\n"
"        automatically includes all subdirectories.\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li><ol><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        You can not separate two different locations and still store them on a\n"
"        single partition (logical, that is - with Volume Management physical\n"
"        partitions <e>can</e> hold several logical ones), so you can't put both\n"
"        <path>/usr</path> and <path>/opt</path> on a single location.\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Some locations also require special attention:\n"
"    "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li><ol><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        The <path>/dev</path> location will already be separated from the main\n"
"        file system by the device manager, so you don't need to devote a\n"
"        specific partition for <path>/dev</path>.\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li><ol><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:128
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        The <path>/tmp</path> and <path>/var/tmp</path> locations are used for\n"
"        temporary file storage. Although the content of these locations is slim\n"
"        in most situations, it can grow exponentially. For instance, during the\n"
"        installation of software through Portage, <path>/var/tmp/portage</path>\n"
"        is used and can require up to a few gigabytes (!) of space.\n"
"      "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:137
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Ask yourself if you really need that nifty file system feature: using Volume\n"
"    Management or (Software) RAID does require more work. Without much guidance,\n"
"    you might lose too much time stabbing at storage related problems.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:142
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Many backup solutions are file system independant, but some of them aren't.\n"
"    If the backup storage is limited but you are using a file system dependant\n"
"    solution, make sure that the total amount of data that it will backup\n"
"    doesn't exceed the dedicated backup storage size.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:150
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"We will discuss the more advanced storage solutions in more detail in a\n"
"different part of this book, but to make you aware of the possibilities we'll\n"
"give a quick rundown of those features first. We won't integrate these solutions\n"
"with the installation procedure though as that would complicate things too much.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:159
#, no-wrap
msgid "RAID arrays"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RAID stands for <e>Redundant Array of Inexpensive Disks</e> and is a well-known\n"
"way of putting disks together. There are several RAID levels defined:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:169
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <e>RAID-Linear</e> places two (or more) disks next to each other and let the\n"
"    user view them as if those disks were a single one. At first, all data is\n"
"    written to the first disk. Once that disk is filled, the second disk is\n"
"    used, etc.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <e>RAID-0</e> is also called <e>striping</e>: unlike with RAID-Linear data\n"
"    is first partitioned after which each 'stripe' of data is written to a disk.\n"
"    Therefore data written to a RAID-0 array is stored across all disks.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <e>RAID-1</e>, also known as <e>mirroring</e>, places all data written to\n"
"    the array on <e>all disks</e>. In other words, each member of the RAID-1\n"
"    array is an exact copy of the others.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:185
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    <e>RAID-5</e> requires at least three disks. We'll explain its inner\n"
"    workings for three disks, but more than three is perfectly possible as well.\n"
"    When data is sent to the array, it is partitioned. For each two parts of\n"
"    data, a simple <e>checksum</e> is created, so we have three data segments.\n"
"    Those three segments are then stored to a disk. If one of the segments is\n"
"    lost, it can be retrieved from the other two segments if necessary.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:195
#, no-wrap
msgid "Other RAID levels exists but are less frequently used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:199
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RAID arrays are interesting when you need high availability of your data. For\n"
"instance, with RAID-1, if one of the disks crashes, the other one takes over.\n"
"Something similar happens with RAID-5: if one of the disks crashes, the other\n"
"disks can work together to generate the data that was stored on the\n"
"malfunctioning disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:207
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you have a true hardware RAID card, using RAID within Linux (or any other\n"
"Operating System for that matter) does not require any input at all: the\n"
"operating system does not handle anything RAID-related. You only see the result,\n"
"the hardware RAID card handles all the rest.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:214
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Pseudo-hardware RAID cards offer various RAID-related services but still require\n"
"some (or a lot) of operating system input. Such cards therefore require a good\n"
"working driver and perhaps even a few tools. Although they aren't as transparent\n"
"as true hardware RAID cards, they still beat the software RAID.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:221
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Software RAID allows users to benefit from most of the RAID functionality\n"
"without requiring any specific hardware. This does require the operating system\n"
"to handle all the RAID-related tasks, requiring some computing time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:227
#, no-wrap
msgid "Information about using Software RAID is discussed further in this book.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:233
#, no-wrap
msgid "Logical Volume Management"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:237
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Unlike RAID, which is most often used for redundancy, LVM allows the user to\n"
"maximise the flexibility of his storage. Basically LVM (actually, LVM2) should\n"
"be seen as a layer in between the physical storage (the disks) and the logical\n"
"view (the file system).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:244
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"With LVM, you create <e>logical volumes</e> (partitions) which hold the file \n"
"systems. One or more logical volumes are stored on a <e>volume group</e> which \n"
"is nothing more than a collection of <e>physical volumes</e> (partitions). A\n"
"physical volume is an entire disk, or a partition, controller by LVM.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:251
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The LVM software offers services on top of this intermediate layer. For\n"
"instance, you can `spread' data across several partitions (like RAID-Linear or\n"
"RAID-0), or have several logical partitions on a single physical one. But that's\n"
"not it. LVM allows you to add (or remove) physical volumes from a volume group\n"
"without affecting the logical volumes (unless of course the logical volumes\n"
"require more space than the volume group has to offer), move data from one disk\n"
"to another without requiring any manual copy procedure or take a snapshot of an\n"
"entire file system without really having to take a full copy of the system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:262
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"These (and more) features make LVM a powerful tool of many system\n"
"administrators.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "Information about LVM2 is discussed further in this book.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:273
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preparing the devices"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:277
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before you can start creating the necessary partitions, you need to make sure\n"
"that the Linux Operating System can work with your hardware. If the installation\n"
"CD that you used to boot didn't automatically detect your hardware, you will\n"
"need to load the appropriate support manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-install-storage.xml:284
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Although we can start by educating you how the Linux kernel addresses the disks\n"
"(like <path>/dev/hd*</path> for IDE, <path>/dev/sd*</path> for SCSI and Serial\n"
"ATA, ...) and what logic is behind it, we will leave this for another document\n"
"(or perhaps a later chapter :) and immediately tell you how to discover where\n"
"your disks are.\n"
msgstr ""

